aditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."],"variants":[{"name":"Hywell","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."]},{"name":"Howell","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Welsh name Hywel , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that name."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Hywel ap Llywelyn was born about 1090, in Wales. He had at least 1 daughter with Marsli Gunter."},"et":{"about 1090–":"umbes 1090–Surnud","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1110–Female":"1110–Surnud","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1090":"1090","about 1090":"umbes 1090","1110":"1110","about 1110":"umbes 1110","Brecon, Breconshire, Wales":"Brecon, Breconshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"about 1090–":"noin 1090–Kuollut","1090–Female":"1090–Kuollut","1110–Female":"1110–Kuollut","1090–Male":"1090–Kuollut","1090":"1090","about 1090":"noin 1090","1110":"1110","about 1110":"noin 1110","Brecon, Breconshire, Wales":"Brecon, Breconshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales"},"fr":{"about 1090–":"environ 1090–Décédé","1090–Female":"1090–Décédée","1110–Female":"1110–Décédée","1090–Male":"1090–Décédé","1090":"1090","about 1090":"environ 1090","1110":"1110","about 1110":"environ 1110","Brecon, Breconshire, Wales":"Brecon, Breconshire, Galles","Wales":"Galles","lifeSummary":"Hywel ap Llywelyn est né environ 1090, à Galles. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Marsli Gunter."},"de":{"about 1090–":"um 1090–Verstorben","1090–Female":"1090–Verstorben","1110–Female":"1110–Verstorben","1090–Male":"1090–Verstorben","1090":"1090","about 1090":"um 1090","1110":"1110","about 1110":"um 1110","Brecon, Breconshire, Wales":"Brecon, Breconshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","lifeSummary":"Hywel ap Llywelyn wurde um 1090 in Wales geboren. Er hatte mit Marsli Gunter mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":